  "prompt": "When can Indian courts take suo motu action?",
  "response": "Indian courts can take suo motu (on their own motion) action in several specific circumstances:\n\n1. Public Interest Litigation (PIL)\n- When fundamental rights are being violated\n- To address systemic issues affecting large sections of society\n- To protect marginalized or vulnerable groups\n\n2. Human Rights Cases\n- Addressing human rights violations\n- Protecting citizens from state or institutional abuse\n- Ensuring basic human dignity\n\n3. Environmental Protection\n- Taking cognizance of environmental degradation\n- Addressing issues of pollution, forest conservation\n- Protecting ecological balance\n\n4. Prison Reforms\n- Investigating prison conditions\n- Addressing inmates' rights and welfare\n- Monitoring prison administration\n\n5. Judicial Oversight\n- Monitoring implementation of court orders\n- Ensuring compliance with legal directives\n- Addressing judicial or administrative lapses\n\n6. Child Rights and Protection\n- Preventing child abuse\n- Addressing issues of child labor\n- Protecting children's welfare\n\n7. Social Justice Issues\n- Addressing discrimination\n- Protecting vulnerable sections of society\n- Ensuring equal treatment under law\n\n8. Cases Involving Serious Misconduct\n- Addressing corruption\n- Investigating official irregularities\n- Protecting public interest\n\nThe Supreme Court and High Courts typically exercise this power under Article 32 and Article 226 of the Indian Constitution.",
